  "prompt": "Why is it not possible for one to use 4 pairs of dry cells especially 12 volts to start a car when 12 volts of a wet cell can start a car?",
  "response": "Using dry cell batteries (like AA or D batteries) to start a car presents several challenges compared to using a lead-acid wet cell battery, even if the total voltage is the same. Here's why:\n\n1. **Current Capacity**: Car starters require a significant amount of current to crank the engine\u2014often between 150 to 200 amps or more, depending on the vehicle and its conditions. Dry cell batteries, such as alkaline batteries, are not designed to provide such high currents. They have higher internal resistance and can\u2019t deliver the high current needed for starting an engine, which is why it is impractical to use multiple pairs of dry cells.\n\n2. **Amp-Hour Rating**: Lead-acid batteries are designed specifically for high discharge rates, meaning they can provide a large amount of current for a short time (which is needed to start the engine) without significant voltage drop. Dry cells typically have a much lower amp-hour rating, meaning they can\u2019t sustain a high-current draw for long periods without depleting rapidly.\n\n3. **Construction and Design**: Wet cell batteries are constructed to handle the stress of high current draw. They can tolerate the thermal and chemical reactions that occur during this process. In contrast, dry cell batteries lack the same robustness; excessive current draw can lead to overheating, leakage of chemicals, or even rupture.\n\n4. **Voltage Under Load**: While you might have the required voltage from combining dry cells to create 12 volts, the voltage can drop significantly under the heavy load of a starter motor because of their internal resistance. This would result in insufficient voltage to actually start the engine.\n\n5. **Cranking Power**: Car batteries are designed specifically for starting engines, meaning they have a specific construction that allows for quick bursts of energy (cranking power). Dry cells do not have this feature.\n\nIn summary, while you can theoretically connect enough dry cells to produce 12 volts, they would not be able to provide the necessary current and would likely fail to crank the engine effectively. For this reason, automotive applications typically rely on lead-acid batteries or other high-capacity batteries specifically designed to deliver the high currents needed for starting engines.",
